Skalnik has always maintained that his testimony in Dailey’s trial was truthful and that he did not receive any benefits in return.
In a remarkable footnote to the ruling, Chief Judge Ed Carnes acknowledged that Skalnik’s testimony at Dailey’s trial was likely false.
Another issue before the judge concerns what prosecutors knew about Skalnik’s criminal history when they called him to testify at Dailey’s trial.
The state attorney’s office ultimately dropped the charge against him and continued to use him as a jailhouse informant.
Dailey’s attorneys had suspected that the notes belonged to Heyman, who questioned the detective during Dailey’s trial.